1 (5) (I) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OF THIS
2 PARAGRAPH, THE ARBITRATION SHALL CONCLUDE WITH A WRITTEN AWARD THAT
3 SUSTAINS IN ITS ENTIRETY THE LAST, BEST, AND FINAL OFFER OF ONE OF THE
4 PARTIES.
5 (II) BEFORE A WRITTEN AWARD IS ISSUED, BY WRITTEN
6 AGREEMENT SIGNED BY THE REPRESENTATIVES OF THE PARTIES PARTICIPATING IN
7 THE ARBITRATION, THE PARTIES MAY DIRECT THE NEUTRAL ARBITRATOR TO RULE
8 ON SPECIFICALLY IDENTIFIED TOPICS OF BARGAINING.
9 (6) (I) THE NEUTRAL ARBITRATOR SHALL ISSUE A PRELIMINARY
10 WRITTEN AWARD ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 5.
11 (II) THE PRELIMINARY WRITTEN AWARD SHALL ADDRESS ALL
12 PROVISIONS THAT EACH PARTY PROPOSED IN ITS RESPECTIVE FINAL POSITION FOR
13 INCLUSION IN A MEMORANDUM OF UNDERSTANDING.
14 (III) WITHIN 5 BUSINESS DAYS AFTER RECEIPT OF THE
15 PRELIMINARY WRITTEN AWARD, THE PARTIES SHALL REVIEW THE AWARD AND MAY
16 SEVERALLY OR MUTUALLY REQUEST CHANGES OR ADJUSTMENTS IN THE AWARD.
17 (IV) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 15, THE NEUTRAL ARBITRATOR
18 SHALL ISSUE A FINAL WRITTEN AWARD IN WHICH THE ARBITRATOR:
19 1. SHALL ORDER IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LAST, BEST,
20 AND FINAL OFFER OF EITHER PARTY IN ITS ENTIRETY, INCORPORATING ANY
21 VOLUNTARILY AGREED–TO TERMS BETWEEN THE PARTIES; AND
22 2. SHALL INCLUDE:
23 A. ANY VOLUNTARILY AGREED–TO TERMS BETWEEN THE
24 PARTIES; AND
25 B. ANY PRIOR TERM THAT BY AGREEMENT IS NOT TO BE
26 CHANGED FOR THE NEXT FISCAL YEAR.
27 (V) AFTER DECEMBER 15, IF REQUESTED BY EITHER PARTY,
28 THE NEUTRAL ARBITRATOR SHALL ISSUE BY JANUARY 20 OF THE IMMEDIATELY
29 FOLLOWING YEAR A STATEMENT OF REASONS FOR THE FINAL WRITTEN AWARD.
30 (7) THE NEUTRAL ARBITRATOR SHALL CONSIDER THE FOLLOWING
31 WHEN DEVELOPING A WRITTEN AWARD:

12 HOUSE BILL 604
1 (I) THE LAWFUL AUTHORITY OF THE EMPLOYER, INCLUDING
2 THE OBLIGATION OF THE EMPLOYER TO USE SPECIAL FUNDS ONLY FOR
3 AUTHORIZED PURPOSES UNDER LIMITATIONS IMPOSED BY FEDERAL OR STATE LAW;
4 (II) STIPULATIONS OF THE PARTIES;
5 (III) THE INTERESTS AND WELFARE OF THE PUBLIC;
6 (IV) THE FINANCIAL ABILITY OF THE EMPLOYER TO MEET
7 COSTS, WITHOUT THE PREMISE THAT THE EMPLOYER MAY NEED TO INCREASE OR
8 IMPOSE NEW TAXES, FEES, OR CHARGES, OR DEVELOP OTHER SOURCES OF REVENUE
9 OR TRANSFER FUNDS FROM THE REVENUE STABILIZATION ACCOUNT ESTABLISHED
10 UNDER § 7–311 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE;
11 (V) THE PRESENT AND FUTURE GENERAL ECONOMIC
12 CONDITION OF THE STATE OR STATE INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION;
13 (VI) COMPARISONS OF WAGES, HOURS, AND CONDITIONS OF
14 EMPLOYMENT OF THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED WITH ARBITRATION WITH THE WAGES,
15 HOURS, AND CONDITIONS OF EMPLOYMENT OF OTHER EMPLOYEES PERFORMING
16 SIMILAR SERVICES IN PUBLIC EMPLOYMENT IN ADJACENT STATES;
17 (VII) COMPARISONS OF COLLECTIVE BARGAINING PATTERNS IN
18 OTHER STATES AND AMONG COUNTY EMPLOYEES IN THE STATE;
19 (VIII) CONSUMER PRICES FOR GOODS AND SERVICES AS DEFINED
20 BY PUBLIC AND PRIVATE SOURCES;
21 (IX) THE OVERALL COMPENSATION PRESENTLY RECEIVED BY
22 THE EMPLOYEES, INCLUDING DIRECT WAGE COMPENSATION, VACATION, HOLIDAYS,
23 EXCUSED TIME OFF, INSURANCE AND PENSIONS COSTS, MEDICAL AND
24 HOSPITALIZATION BENEFITS, THE CONTINUITY AND STABILITY OF EMPLOYMENT,
25 AND ALL OTHER RECEIVED BENEFITS;
26 (X) CHANGES IN ANY OF THE FOREGOING CIRCUMSTANCES
27 DURING THE PENDENCY OF THE ARBITRATION; AND
28 (XI) OTHER FACTORS THAT ARE NORMALLY OR TRADITIONALLY
29 TAKEN INTO CONSIDERATION IN THE DETERMINATION OF WAGES, HOURS, AND
30 CONDITIONS OF EMPLOYMENT THROUGH VOLUNTARY COLLECTIVE BARGAINING,
31 MEDIATION, ARBITRATION, OR OTHERWISE BETWEEN THE PARTIES IN PUBLIC
32 SERVICE OR PRIVATE EMPLOYMENT.

